The paper deals with complexity classes and oracles, which are central topics in computational complexity theory. Specifically, it investigates the behavior of polynomial-time random oracles and their implications on separating complexity classes. This makes cs.CC (Computational Complexity) the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves cryptography and information theory, which suggests cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) and cs.IT (Information Theory) as likely sub-categories. The use of martingales and resource-bounded measure may also relate to cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science).
